= 1967, alone.

{!


<div class="typewriter dialogue1" id="dialogue1">!}

<img src="img/background/death.webp" class="death">


Life ended this day. 

The life that you knew.

Everything that you had known was shattered by six bullets. 

Two and four in your two parents.

Blood spilled on the pavement, the wind ripping away the last warmth you felt. 

You felt nothing else in this place to move forward.

As you moved home, your life had been irrevocably derailed.

You needed to find one way out.

{!</div>!}

- @you: Debug skip to promises.
- @1967_justice: You needed to bring those that would do such a thing to justice.
- @1967_vengeance: You swore that you will have vengeance for what happened.
- @1967_never: You saw that nothing like this should ever happen to anyone.


@1967_justice
on-arrival: order += 1
go-to: 1977

@1967_vengeance
on-arrival: liberty += 1; moral_compass -= 5
go-to: 1977

@1967_never
on-arrival: moral_compass += 10
go-to: 1977


@1977
new-page: true
on-display: {!
    introDialogue();

!}
set-bg: img/background/summer.jpg

= 1977, Walk on a summer's day

{!<div class="typewriter">!}

For weeks, you seemed like a ghost. Someone that could talk and sometimes answer, but to the world around you?

You were a shell of a human. 

A boy with a flickering soul, ready to be extinguished at any moment. 

A will burning without fuel.

The first year is often the most difficult. Where theory must stand against the waves of reality. Yet when you brave it alone, all you can do is tread and pray for the best. 

Sure, Alfred always was an anchor, yet you found yourself reaching out to another hand through the waters. 

Just a girl.

A girl named Andrea Beaumont.

It’s funny, how she walked up to you in the parking lots of Gotham Academy when everyone else seemed hellbent on staying out of your way. How the first thing she said to the weeping 1st grader wasn’t “Do you need someone to talk to?”, “It’ll get better,” or all the other empty platitudes thrown your way by peers and teachers alike. She just sat down next to you on the curb, placed her backpack next to yours, and told you bluntly as all children do,

“It’s okay, my mom’s dead too.” 

You didn’t say much back to her that day. The fresh memory of blood spilling on concrete was too much for you to care about anyone else, let alone another kid your age who would always tag along while you waited for Alfred there on out.  You didn’t get it. Why me? Why her? Maybe it was just the fact that between the ruby bricks of private school, there was at least one person who wouldn’t soothe your pain, but instead, truly understand it. 

She told you she was Andrea, but her friends called her Andi. She spent her weekends watching TV, cutting up her Barbies’ dresses and squiggling markers on their faces to look like the Grey Ghost. You liked the Grey Ghost too. And so, for the first time in a while, the two of you had a conversation. A real one with more than just Andi listing off how her funeral proceedings were going and how boring all of it was. 

{!</div>!}

- @1977_2: She was your first friend.

@1977_2
subtitle: And she had no reason to be.
new-page: true
on-display: {!
    introDialogue();
!}

= 1977, Walk on a summer's day

{!<div class="typewriter">!}

From then on out, she was always a shoulder you could count on. 

Your helping hand in the nights of grief. 

From the moments in doubts, to the years in shadow, to those rebuilding, she was the first to trust.

You didn’t deserve the butterflies in your stomach you felt when you were next to her. 

You didn’t deserve the warmth of her presence thawing your grieving, numb heart. 

You’d swear you’d never be happy again, that you’d used your hole of eternal suffering to avenge what you swore to your parents, that the only way forward was alone. 

Out there, you are bewildered feeling something you wanted that wasn’t a duty. 

To want something, or someone you’d need.

You felt the tug of two hands, one cold, one warmer. A pull from the past and the future. Andrea was there, waiting patiently through one side of the tunnel. She wished to bring you to the old continent, to let your past flow behind you. A fresh start. A new beginning of trust, and love. You felt the clasp of her soft, chill hand. 

And you chose to let go.

You couldn’t abandon this home. No matter how far you could run away from it, the pain would not fade. Gotham chained you to the ground.

This was a place you could not leave.

{!</div>!}

- @1979: It is my duty and curse. To fight for those that cannot.

@1979
