= 1981, David’s escape:

{!<div class="typewriter dialogue4">!}

As you became David Cain’s trusted lieutenant, what used to only be professional issues slowly mellowed as both of you learned more about each other.

You learned you did have quite a bit in common, both orphans that have tried to find a place in their life without any clear guide. 

Yet, it’s very clear that his origin as a child abandoned from the Korean war adopted by an American family made clear that there is no bottom to misery.

Still, knowing him better, while he practiced neutrality, he seemed more and more disillusioned by the work he did. 

He had hopes, all his life, hopes of making things better. Hopes dashed in his homeland, a country that had abandoned him that then saw him as a foreign agent for daring to ask for change in a fascist regime. Hopes that seem to fade yet again as the league seemed more interested in the minutia of ideals than in actions.

One night, knocking on your door. He would come to you to inform you of his immediate leave. This did not surprise you however, what did was the fact he intended to leave with his daughter Cassandra.

He told you his story, the whole story. 

From his activism against the South Korean dictatorship to his fascination for the league of assassins, his falling in love with Shiva, a child that expedited a marriage which saw both clash over their superficially similar but deeply different vision for the world. 

All of those could be accepted, could be tolerated.

But for one thing.

“Ra’s wanted to turn my daughter into a killing machine. They have warped her brain, made her kill as just a child. Shiva said it’s a necessary sacrifice, I will not abandon my child.” 

{!</div>
!}

- @stop_david: You tried to stop Him, Physically.
- @talk_david: You tried to talk him out of his plan.
- @let_david_go: You decided to let him go and stay silent on the issue.
- @david_confront: You decided to let him go and confronted Shiva and Ra’s about the issue he raised

@stop_david
