set-bg: img/background/grayson.jpg

{!<div class="typewriter dialogue7">!}

= The Grayson's 

You’ve seen the Graysons many times before. They’re always a delight when they come to town. The carefully staged acrobatics of human form leaping through the air as if it were water, that stuff always amazed you. Two seats are now empty today, yet for a while, there’s something that just feels… off since the beginning of this show.

Their smiles are just a bit more fake than they should be. The jumps were just slightly off sync, the presentation just a bit too saccharine. Cracks were showing through the veneer of the impeccable flying Graysons.

For a moment it felt like rose tinted glasses slimping off, like a growing itch howling to be scratched. The lights dimmed. Two parents on their toes leaped from the height of clouds. And they fell. 

There was not a sound.

And then there was a crunch.

Only then did the lights come back up. Where in place of a happy family bowing down to the crowd were two limp bodies in front of their child. He stared at them twenty feet off the ground, shaking, unsure what to do, what to say, frozen in place, as the world could do nothing but gawk at his every move. 

You and the hundreds of other onlookers were promptly escorted off the premises. As you looked back from the performance turned crime scene, police coddled a tween in blankets, whose only words he would speak were cries of anguish towards the family stolen right in front of him. 

You spoke to GPD the next day. Told them if he needed a home, they should contact you pronto. That Grayson kid needs someone to help him. He needs someone to support him. Someone to protect him.

You promptly signed the forms to adopt Richard Grayson the following week. At first, he seemed bewildered that you would take him in. His house was too big. The floors are too shiny. The plants are too tightly trimmed. He didn’t talk to you much in between the police interrogations and the child support check ins. It was like taking care of a ghost barely breathing. 

You got through to him though, eventually. You got to know Richard, or Dick as his parents called him. He became more restless, always sliding down stair rails and cracking quips with Alfred. Eventually, he took up a hood on his head to fight crime. 

The reflection was crystal clear. This kid could do a lot of good, he just needed the right guidance.

Taking him as your son, with his enthusiastic consent, the robin will spread his wings and sing in the skies.

He only had to swear on it, before me, before the city.

Two heroes in the night. 


{!</div>!}

- @grayson_righteous: …And swear that we two will fight together against crime and corruption and never swerve from the path of righteousness.
- @grayson_liberty: …And swear that we two will fight together against crime and corruption and never swerve from the path of Justice.
- @grayson_order: …And swear that we two will fight together against crime and corruption and never question the order I am given.

@grayson_righteous
go-to: 1984_end

@grayson_liberty
go-to: 1984_end

@grayson_order
go-to: 1984_end

@1984_end
new-page: true
on-display: {!

introDialogue();

