set-bg: img/background/harveydent.webp

= Harvey Dent

{!<div class="typewriter dialogue8">!}
The fight for justice is a lonely battle. Yet, the knowledge that someone is beside you, someone will help, it’s something that makes each night of sleep feel a little less guilty. 

After Andrea, you never trusted yourself to find someone like that again. 

You’ve attended many trials in your life. Mostly as a spectator. Sometimes as a witness. Once as a juror. Almost all of them were loaded to the brim with bribes openly hanging from everyone’s pockets. But not this time. 

An especially fiery assistant county prosecutor caught your eye bickering with the judge. While most who passed the bar here used it as a way to become a vehicle for corruption, he seemed more invested in finding the truth of the crime of a simple robbery than either the police, the judge he was giving an earful to, or even the defendant were.

You reached out to him after the trial. Both of you knew the result from the get go, but he seemed crushed by it anyways. As you consoled the man, you exchanged cards. Reading his, you learned the assistant’s name was Harvey Apollo Dent. You were ready to just leave it at that; the past taught you not to trust. 

But as always, trust doesn’t work on Wayne time alone. 

He’d call your number on your card every now and then to ask about financial business. Inevitably, you’d have to do the same when it came to the law. He was smart, as devoted to justice as you were. As terrible of a sleeper you were. You found in each other the same drive to help people, the same struggle with so many people needing your help, but with so little time to help them. Against your better judgement, you’d come to know Harvey as your friend. 

Still, while on the stand his good looks and boundless confidence made him seem like the archetypical movie law man of the pulpit, meeting him in his office was like talking to an entirely different man. His desk was haphazardly scattered with papers, books piled against his desk up against each other, reaching the height of his waist. Harvey Dent just seemed tired, feeling like he could never do enough. Be enough. That so many things were out of his control.

As you mentioned the strange case of the Graysons, he assured you he’d do all he could to catch him. You found the culprit as Batman. Caught the man redhanded with the law ready to put him behind bars as Handsome Harv worked tirelessly on the one case he promised to you would be in good hands. 

The killer of the Graysons managed to get out on a technicality.

There’s not much a mere man can do against a broken system after all. It didn’t make the sting of it hurt any less. You find yourself pulled between two worlds. One where a swindler sold a grand lie, only to disappear once the charade was revealed, and one where not even an orphan could ever forgive the great sins of personal disgrace. 

But that’s what failure is for, right? The proof of concept is still here. On the ground and on the pulpit, the power it truly had was clear as day. You only had to own it, to work out the kinks.

{!</div>!}

- @harvey_law: I think our main goal, before any other, should be to work on those issues of the law. So many crimes are being committed each day, we would do a disservice not to act now and act decisively.
- @harvey_relation: I think that if such a relationship is to remain strong, I have to keep tighter contact with Harvey. He is a massive asset and he needs to be cherished considering what happened to others in the past.
- @harvey_dick: I think this issue between him and Dick can still be patched over. This is just a failure of communication. Harvey thought that Dick already hates him and Dick feels like Harvey is heartless for not mentioning the problem. We can’t build anything on hurt feelings.

@harvey_law
on-arrival: crime_rate -= 5
go-to: 1985_choice

