{!<div class="typewriter">!}

= Independence

“You’re not doing enough, dad.”

This was a sentence that Dick has been saying at an ever increasing pace since a few years now. For a while it felt like the natural effect of becoming a teenager. However, the opposition wasn’t as much a general rebellion against authority as a feeling you’re simply not getting it.

“I just think you don’t get what people go through! You’ve never had to worry about your next meal, or the water going out, or hell, even just paying rent! You just can’t see people need just so much more.”

Clinging crystal glasses with the crust of society, the sizzle of champagne, the look on their smile is clear. All teeth, most proud of achieving their places, not through luck, not through inheritance, only through their own great skills. Just like you? Isn’t it how it is?

You did work your ass off to get to the place you are? They don’t know just how hard it is to own a multinational company while also doing the hard work of stemming the waves of crime in the city after all. And yet… There's something disgusting here. Even without their brow full of sweat and their purse so heavy, they claim they just can’t do more.

“Look dad… Bruce. I’m ripping off the band-aid. I think it’s time I do what I should have done since the start. I can’t thank you enough for all the help you’ve given me - I mean not just the whole adopting me thing, but everything. I don’t know how much it would take to repay it back, if I even COULD in the first place but…”

“I don’t think we can’t continue working like this, dad. Together. In the city. We’re driving ourselves apart.”

You gave Dick an allowance and the best suit he could dream off to fight in his home city, Blüdhaven. For those that know, the message was to try and spread the fight against crime out of the border of just one city. Yet, even after the hug and the leave, it’s clear this wasn’t the break you had wanted. 

Dick probably would never have fully accustomed himself with the kind of life you had brought him in. Too many false smiles, too many lies, too many handshakes with snakes. The irony of him leaving the mansion to still be financially dependent on you isn’t lost on you either. If he justify it on the fact he’s giving away 90% of what you’re giving him, then all power to him.

Yet, eating with one person less, another room empty, hearing the echoes slightly louder… He had to get out someday, find his way out, find his way to be free. To make his own way. He changed a lot, he will continue to. 

Being a parent is the hardest job in the world. He needed you being here, you helping him, but perhaps not advising him. You think he knew rather quickly what he wanted to do and in a way, he’ll be much brighter than you are, as he took what you knew to make even more. 

{!</div>!}

- @dick_liberty: I was perhaps a bit too protective of him. He had seen so many things and I had the power to protect him from those things. Yet he didn’t want to protect himself, he needed to help others. I need to let people breathe.
- @dick_sanity: I never saw anyone with as much trust in himself as him. There are doubts, some I still share, that I fear may be the only thing tearing me down. I can’t let myself do nothing fearing what I may do wrong.
- @dick_morality: I think there is something that separates him from other kids. I’ve been bitter, I may have become a monster if I had not been in such good company. He didn’t need that, he simply wanted to be the best for others. This is all that matters.

