{!<div class="typewriter">!}

= Replacement

Fighting alone. This is what you were trained to do. To be a lone vigil in the night. To be the cog in the machine which shall not break. To be marching in the desert guided by a single star.

As you are once more alone, you feel a tension return. You had felt it, how easier it has been to work with someone else for those 5 years. However, it’s only now you can really feel just how reliant you have become on Dick’s help. A second set of eyes, hands, someone to trust to do as much good as you could, or at least close to it. But… No… That wasn’t just it. There's something more.

Even as crime does not seem as overwhelming as it used to be, you can feel the grinding of the gears. As much as you would prefer not to have them face those pains… Dick proved that they are seeking those themselves even if you try to protect them. They just need your help. No… You needed theirs.

There’s two you’ve seen. Two rebels without cause. Two punks lost on what to do with themselves. One trying to desperately break from the golden cage she’s found herself in and the other simply trying to survive, both unable to know what to do. They only need to find their way. You thought you had found one yourself, now you’re not so sure.

Dinah Lance has been breaking bad for a while. It seems the money that you gave to her mother has driven a wedge between the two. Dinah Drake began to pamper her daughter, to use the wealth she now had to work even more for others and her daughter only wanted to be loved, to feel something. 

She has seen you as what her mother used to be, in what she wanted to become, what she felt pressured to be and what she deeply didn’t want to end up as. She wanted to find her place in this world, her own place, wherever it may be. Even going so far as to talk with the cat. Trying to reach a seventeen year old girl who’s scream broke glass was a challenge in itself. 

The black canary was both feather of freedom and tar coated. She had a legacy to live by, even as her own mother said the contrary. She wanted to be herself, to be her own vision of what best she saw in her parents, in those she looked up to so much. She wanted to finally break the mistake that had been made over and over again, making brand new ones.

Perhaps you really are nuts, taking in not only her but also the most troubled kid in the orphanage. The superintendent said that those kinds of kids, that never knew their parents, those that only knew the harshness of life, that had no one to talk to, no one to speak words that feel genuine, to hear answers that took into account what they think.

You could see it in his eyes, when you revealed the wings of the bat, there was something inside that could be said in words. You spread your hand, asking him to be at your side, he took it. He felt in that dark cloak someone to be, someone strong, someone that will no longer have to fear for his life, for his mind. Someone who was no longer being beaten up. Someone that can be more than who he was, Someone else.

You saw many links of someone rough in him. As someone finally free striking those that had failed with furious anger. You knew you needed to help him. He already knew what he wanted to do, he was the person he finally could be. He wanted to do everything all at once. To do all the good that needed to be done. It’s destroying himself.

They needed you. They are afraid, they fear being alone again, to be left out of life, to be seen as a burden. They are trying to prove to you their worth even though they are already worthy. They want to help others, to do good, to be free and fulfilled, that all that matters. They were lost, in some way, they still are. They wish to be the best they can be but having tasted the bitterness of the grey line between good and evil, they don’t know where the edge should fall.

They are worth your support by their own lives, they really do, not because of their powers, because of their drive, but by who they are. You’ve been distant, maybe too focused on your mission rather than who you need to be with to fulfill it. You can’t march on alone, not after being lost for so long. You need to help them. You’ve heard those doubts, those voices without breath.

Why preach in a desert? Did you want to beat people so they could finally escape their nights? They are already loving your image much more than your ideal. Why are you doing this by duty and not by want? Is it too soon or already too late? Is it true or done for your sake? Bruce, If you can’t help them, who could save you?

You’ve burned your hands with the fire. It’s a pain that will not fade. It’s the curse of seeing the truth, to never be able to ignore it. It’s the curse of knowing all your acts and consequences are yours. The curse of being free. It’s a pain you cannot bear alone.

You’ve seen your reflection in their eyes. You can’t be blind to it. You’ve been brought through suffering they’ve only had too much of. You need to light the fires, even if it burns yourself.

{!</div>!}

- @replacement_bruce: I put on the cape so I wouldn't have to feel it anymore. So the grief would have somewhere to go. I see now that was never going to work. You can't build something living out of what you're running from.
- @replacement_jason: Anger is not a compass. I know because I've tried to use it as one. Every time you hit someone out of fury rather than necessity, you're not protecting anyone. You're just making sure the pain lands somewhere. Eventually, it will land back on you.
- @replacement_dinah: Those that truly raised us never stopped caring. They just forgot that care isn't something you construct for someone else. You don't have to carry their name or their cause. You only have to carry what you actually believe in. That's harder than it sounds. It’s something I still struggle with.

