{!<div class="typewriter">!}

= The Dark Year 

Things have not improved since the arrival of Quincy Sharp. No, they became much worse. Militarization, privatisation of prisons, violence on every part of society. The policemen dressed up as the military, no, PMC’s taking their insurgent into working camps. What used to be a city now looked like a zone of war undergoing pacification.

6 years of work to create a relationship between the police and population made by Gordon destroyed in an instant. For the mayor, he had become a liability.

Under the new police chief, Lyle Bolton, crime will be answered by fire and brimstone, destroying everything in their path to achieve their goal of ending crime in the city. No innocent will be spared in the fight for order. To that end, the Bat’s services are no longer required.

You are now an outlaw for all intent and purposes, much like the proverbial canary, the bat being removed became a show of realization for the average person in the city that things have taken a turn for the cruel. The journals, the tv could say that the violence is justified, when a friend of a friend gets hurt, it’s hard to believe their words.

Gaps, fractures are appearing in society. People are blaming each other, people are no longer speaking to one another, they are shouting, they are screaming at each other, at everything. Understanding is lost, there's only pain and physical communication.

The wound bursted. The Prisons, those places are overstuffed, overcruel, overpriced, understaffed and undersized, the dam as broken. The criminals are back on the streets, the circus is back in town.

Jason said that he had stolen before, to feed himself, feed people he cared about, all because the rules were set up for him to be unable to follow them without suffering or making others suffer. When the law becomes unjust, isn’t it only fair to break it in turn? To right what became wrong?

Even acting against the law, you need act, you need to do something to save the city before it breaks apart on itself.

{!</div>!}

- @dark_year_safe:  I need to help the people stay safe, I need to save them from the wind or they’ll fall. This is where wealth needs to act.
- @dark_year_criminal: There's not thirty ways of helping the people against those criminals. We will fight those criminals, may the police like or hate it.

@1991_start_quincy
on-display: {!
    introDialogue();
!}
new-page: true
set-bg: img/background/darkyearrooftops.webp
on-arrival: approval_rating_bruce -= 5

{!<div class="typewriter">!}

= The Dark Year

Perhaps, this was a mistake.

The plan was flawed, or maybe it was the execution, either way, the situation is rapidly degrading. Quincy is going too hard to fast on too many things all at once. When everything was a nail to him, he needed as many hammers as he could get his hands on.

Perhaps he was much too enthusiastic in making out of all the police force his own legions of Batman to fight against crime. They don’t know what they are doing. They have weapons of war, orders to shoot, they don’t know how to fix, only how to break.

James couldn’t allow it to continue. With his resignation blew away most of the influence you had to keep the worst excesses of this police. Instead of a stone to sharpen against, they will find a rock to throw at their adversary, Lyle Bolton.

It was said that by the end of his term, Hamilton Hill was deeply unpopular. That’s wrong, seeing the protest, seeing the shoots, seeing the vandalism. That’s real hate, that’s true unpopularity, that is the show of someone that has lost the mandate of the people and now acted on pure instinct.

It wasn’t just one thing, it wasn’t just putting the prison to sale, it was just locking everyone up, including likely many innocent people in jail, it wasn’t just making them work their stay in bars. It was everything. So much pressure in such a short amount of time let a loud and instant pop all around the town as the prison burst and flowed out to the streets.

Suddenly, for someone who seemed to always have the solution to everything he set himself out to do, Quincy looked particularly powerless and in search of aid right after it had become perhaps too late for him to fix much of anything.

Jason told me that people need things to blow in their faces for them to really realize they are wrong. It’s only when someone breaks something that they start to slow down. When they do irrevocable damage to something they care about deeply. When they think they can’t walk back and are fully responsible for it.

However, Quincy has never met any resistance in his entire life, any time where everything could be turned back as the hands of a clock. For him, this gale has become a death sentence, something it may as well be.

Some won’t forgive your shaking hand with the most unpopular man in Gotham. Yet, their gratitude is less important than their welfare. They deserve everything they can receive, then, perhaps, it will be a good place to start. 

{!</div>!}

- @dark_year_quincy_criminal: I’ll make it clear to Quincy Sharp, Either the police change now or the people will make it change by force. Batman will deal with the rogue elements, this can’t continue.
- @dark_year_quincy_people: Sharp has prejudice in him. He may not show it too publicly, but I can see it. He needs to give back to the people before they take everything from him. This is no longer up to negotiation.

@dark_year_quincy_criminal
on-arrival: crime_rate -= 15; quincy_crime_rate = 1; batman += 1

Much of the easily reversible policy that had been set was reset. However, before the real hard work could begin, Lyle Bolton mutinied against what he thought was a betrayal of the population. You gladly beat him and took him to court. Gordon has his work cut out for him, but at least he wouldn’t be sandbagged while doing it anymore.

- @1991_end: Next year.

@dark_year_quincy_people
on-arrival: poverty -= 15; bruce += 1

The Sharp social contract would usually be rather popular. After all, people usually liked having jobs, having money, not being in the gutter. That’s what you marketed it as, that’s what some saw it as. Still, for so many, all they could see was the reflection of the face-shields of the military police.

- @1991_end: Next year.

@dark_year_safe
on-arrival: bruce += 1; approval_rating_bruce += 5; poverty -= 5

You spend much to help the population avoid its terminal fall. It’s like plugging a massive hole and yet, you feel like you made a change and people saw it.

- @1991_end: Next year.

